🧠 Architecture (What we’re building)

Spring Boot App (Java TrustStore)
        ↓  (TCPS + SSL)
Oracle DB (SSL enabled by DBA)

👉 No Oracle Wallet
👉 Java handles SSL using TrustStore


---

👨‍💻 PART 1: WHAT DBA TEAM MUST DO (VERY IMPORTANT)

Before you do anything, DBA must confirm this:


---

✅ 1️⃣ Enable TCPS on Oracle DB

Ask DBA:

> “Please confirm TCPS is enabled and share port + certificates”




---

DBA changes (on DB server):

📍 listener.ora

LISTENER =
  (DESCRIPTION_LIST =
    (DESCRIPTION =
      (ADDRESS = (PROTOCOL = TCPS)(HOST = db-host)(PORT = 2484))
    )
  )


---

📍 sqlnet.ora

SSL_VERSION = 1.2
WALLET_LOCATION = (SOURCE = (METHOD = FILE) (METHOD_DATA = (DIRECTORY = /path/to/db_wallet)))
SSL_CLIENT_AUTHENTICATION = FALSE


---

🧠 Meaning:

DB listens on secure port (2484)

SSL enabled



---

✅ 2️⃣ Provide Certificates to YOU

Ask DBA for:

Root certificate (root.pem)

Intermediate cert (intermediate.pem) (if exists)

Server cert (server-cert.pem)



---

👉 This is mandatory
Without this → you CANNOT proceed


---

👨‍💻 PART 2: YOUR WORK (Spring Boot / App Team)


---

✅ Step 1: Store Certificates

Create folder:

mkdir -p /opt/certs
cd /opt/certs

Place:

root.pem
intermediate.pem
server-cert.pem


---

✅ Step 2: Create Java TrustStore

keytool -import -trustcacerts \
-alias oracle-root \
-file root.pem \
-keystore truststore.jks \
-storepass changeit


---

👉 Add intermediate:

keytool -import -trustcacerts \
-alias oracle-intermediate \
-file intermediate.pem \
-keystore truststore.jks \
-storepass changeit


---

👉 Add server cert:

keytool -import -trustcacerts \
-alias oracle-server \
-file server-cert.pem \
-keystore truststore.jks \
-storepass changeit


---

🔍 What this does:

Creates truststore.jks

Stores trusted certificates



---

🧠 Why:

Java will: 👉 Verify DB identity using this truststore


---

✅ Step 3: Verify TrustStore

keytool -list -keystore truststore.jks -storepass changeit

👉 You should see:

oracle-root ✔

oracle-intermediate ✔

oracle-server ✔



---

✅ Step 4: Configure Spring Boot


---

🔹 Option A: JVM args (BEST PRACTICE)

-Djavax.net.ssl.trustStore=/opt/certs/truststore.jks
-Djavax.net.ssl.trustStorePassword=changeit


---

🔹 Option B: application.properties

spring.datasource.url=jdbc:oracle:thin:@(DESCRIPTION=
 (ADDRESS=(PROTOCOL=tcps)(HOST=db-host)(PORT=2484))
 (CONNECT_DATA=(SERVICE_NAME=your_service))
)
spring.datasource.username=your_user
spring.datasource.password=your_pass


---

✅ Step 5: Force TLS Version (IMPORTANT for audit)

Add:

-Dhttps.protocols=TLSv1.2,TLSv1.3


---

✅ Step 6: Test Connection

Run your app OR simple test:

👉 If working:

No SSL error

Connection successful



---

🧪 HOW TO VALIDATE (VERY IMPORTANT)


---

✅ Enable SSL Debug Logs

Run app with:

-Djavax.net.debug=ssl


---

👉 You should see:

TLSv1.2 handshake

Certificate verified



---

✅ Confirm it's TCPS

Check logs:

(PROTOCOL=tcps)


---

⚠️ COMMON ERRORS + FIXES


---

❌ PKIX path building failed

👉 Cause:

Missing cert


👉 Fix:

Add full chain (root + intermediate)



---

❌ handshake_failure

👉 Cause:

TLS mismatch


👉 Fix:

Force TLS 1.2



---

❌ connection refused

👉 Cause:

TCPS not enabled on DB


👉 Fix: 👉 Ask DBA to confirm port 2484 open


